# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-community-survey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:american-community-survey/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] The **1960 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 179,323,175, an increase of 19 percent over the 151,325,798 persons enumerated during the 1950 census.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] This census's data determined the electoral votes for the 1964 and 1968 presidential elections.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] This was also the last census in which New York was the most populous state.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] Detroit lost 220,000 residents in the 1950s, which remains the record for the largest loss of population between two censuses.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] Approximately 25% of households received a "long form" of the 1960 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 1960 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1960 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:american-community-survey/1960-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2032.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] The **1990 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States to be 248,709,873, an increase of 9.8 percent over the 226,545,805 persons enumerated during the 1980 census.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 1990 census, which contained more than 100 questions.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 1990 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] It was the first census to designate "Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander" as a racial group separate from Asians.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] The census was also the first census to be directed by a woman, Barbara Everitt Bryant.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] To increase black participation in the 1990 United States census, the bureau recruited Bill Cosby, Magic Johnson, Alfre Woodard, and Miss America Debbye Turner as spokespeople.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2062.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] This was the first census since 1880 in which Chicago was not the second-largest city, having been overtaken by Los Angeles.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] As of the 2020 census, Los Angeles has remained the nation's second-largest city.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] This was also the first census in which Wyoming was the least populous state.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] The results of the 1990 census determined the number of seats that each state receives in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 1992 elections.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state has in the Electoral College for the 1992 presidential election.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] Because of population changes, twenty-one states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and thirteen states lost at least one seat.
[src:american-community-survey/1990-united-states-census] The final result involved 19 seats being switched.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The **2000 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States on April 1, 2000, to be 281,421,906, an increase of 13.2 percent over the 248,709,873 people enumerated during the 1990 census.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] This was the twenty-second federal census and was at the time the largest civilly administered peacetime effort in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 2000 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] It would be the last census to include the "long form", since subsequent censuses, starting with the 2010 census, would be "short form" only, with the more detailed questions being replaced by the new American Community Survey.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 2000 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of over 30 million, as well as the first in which two states—California and Texas—recorded populations of more than 20 million.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Microdata from the 2000 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2072.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The U.S. resident population includes the total number of people in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau also enumerated the residents of the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico; its population was 3,808,610, an 8.1% increase over the number from a decade earlier.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Regionally, the South and West experienced the bulk of the nation's population increase: 14,790,890 and 10,411,850, respectively.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] This meant that the mean center of U.S. population moved to Phelps County, Missouri.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The Northeastern United States grew by 2,785,149; the Midwest by 4,724,144.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The results of the census are used to determine how many congressional districts each state is apportioned.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Congress defines the formula, in accordance with Title 2 of the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Code, to reapportion among the states the 435 seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The apportionment population consists of the resident population of the fifty states, plus the overseas military and federal civilian employees and their dependents living with them who could be allocated to a state.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Each member of the House represents a population of about 647,000.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The populations of the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico are excluded from the apportionment population because they do not have voting seats in the U.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Since the first census in 1790, the decennial count has been the basis for the United States representative form of government.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Article I, Section II specifies that "The Number of Representatives shall not exceed one for every thirty Thousand, but each State shall have at Least one Representative." In 1790, each member of the House represented about 34,000 residents.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Since then, the House more than quadrupled in size, and in 1911 the number of representatives was fixed at 435.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Today, each member represents about 20 times as many constituents.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] In the years leading up to the 2000 census, there was substantial controversy over whether the Bureau should adjust census figures based on a follow-up survey, called the post-enumeration survey, of a sample of blocks.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] This recommendation was followed by the Secretary of Commerce (the official in charge of making the determination).
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] After the census was tabulated, Utah challenged the results in two different ways.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Utah was extremely close to gaining a fourth congressional seat, falling 857 people short, which in turn was allocated to North Carolina.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The margin was later shortened to 80 people, after the federal government discovered that it overcounted the population of North Carolina by 2,673 residents.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau counted members of the military and other federal civilian employees serving abroad as residents of their home state but did not count other people living outside the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Utah claimed that people traveling abroad as religious missionaries should be counted as residents and that the failure to do so imposed a burden on Mormon religious practice.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Almost half of all Mormon missionaries, more than 11,000 people, were from Utah; only 102 came from North Carolina.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] If this policy were changed, then Utah would have received an additional seat instead of North Carolina.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] On November 26, 2002, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court ruling that rejected Utah's efforts to have Mormon missionaries counted.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The state of Utah then filed another lawsuit alleging that the statistical methods used in computing the state populations were improper and cost Utah the seat.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau uses a method called imputation to assign a number of residents to addresses where residents cannot be reached after multiple efforts.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] While nationwide the imputation method added 0.4% to the population, the rate in Utah was 0.2%.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The state challenged that the use of imputation violates the Census Act of 1957 and that it also fails the Constitution's requirement in Article I, Section 2 that an "actual enumeration" be used for apportionment.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Evans*, made it to the Supreme Court, but Utah was again defeated.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The census forms did not include any questions regarding sexual orientation, making it impossible to compile data comparing heterosexual and homosexual populations.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] However, two questions *were* asked that allowed same-sex partnerships to be counted.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The questionnaires asked the sex of each person in a household and they asked what the relationship was between each of the members of the household.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Respondents could check "Husband/wife" or "unmarried partner" or a number of other relationships.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Responses were tabulated and the Census Bureau reported that there were more than 658,000 same-sex couples heading households in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] However, only about 25% of gay men and 40% of lesbians are in shared-household partnerships at any one time, according to non-census surveys.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] For every same-sex couple tallied in the census, there could be three to six more homosexual un-partnered individuals who would not be counted as gay.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The census reported that same-sex male couples numbered 336,001 and female same-sex couples numbered 329,522.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Extrapolating from those figures and the surveyed partnering habits of homosexuals, as many as 4.3 million homosexual adults could have been living in the U.S. in 2000.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The exact number cannot be known because the census did not count them specifically.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Bisexual and transgender populations were not counted, either, because there were no questions regarding this information.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Also unavailable is the number of additional same-sex couples living under the same roof as the first, though this applies to additional heterosexual couples as well.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The lack of accurate numbers makes it difficult for lawmakers who are considering legislation on hate crimes or social services for gay families with children.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] It also makes for less accuracy when predicting the fertility of a population.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Another issue that concerned gay rights advocates involved the automatic changing of data during the tabulation process.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] This automatic software data compiling method, called *allocation*, was designed to counteract mistakes and discrepancies in returned questionnaires.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] Forms that were filled out by two same-sex persons who checked the "Husband/wife" relationship box were treated as a discrepancy.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau explained that same-sex "Husband/wife" data samples were changed to "unmarried partner" by computer processing methods in 99% of the cases.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] In the remaining 1%, computer systems used one of two possibilities: a) one of the two listed sexes was changed, making the partnership appear heterosexual, or b) if the two partners were more than 15 years apart in age, they might have been reassigned into a familial parent/child relationship.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] The process of automatic reassignment of same-sex marriage data was initiated so that the Census Bureau would not contravene the Defense of Marriage Act passed in 1996.
[src:american-community-survey/2000-united-states-census] With allocation moving married same-sex couples to the unmarried partner category, social scientists lost information that could have been extracted relating to the social stability of a same-gender couple who identify themselves as married.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:american-community-survey/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The **United States Bicentennial** was a series of celebrations and observances during the mid-1970s that paid tribute to historical events leading up to the creation of the United States as an independent republic.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] It was a central event in the memory of the American Revolution.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Bicentennial culminated on Sunday, July 4, 1976, with the 200th anniversary of the adoption of the Declaration of Independence by the Founding Fathers in the Second Continental Congress.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The United States has historically commemorated the founding as a gesture of patriotism and, at times, as an argument in political battles.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Historian Jonathan Crider points out that in the 1850s, editors and orators, from both Northern and Southern states, claimed their region was the true custodian of the legacy of 1776, as they used the Revolution symbolically in their rhetoric.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The plans for the Bicentennial began when Congress created the **American Revolution Bicentennial Commission** on July 4, 1966.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Initially, the Bicentennial celebration was planned as a single city exposition (titled Expo '76) that would be staged in either Philadelphia or Boston.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] After 6½ years of tumultuous debate, the Commission recommended that there should not be a single event.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Congress dissolved it on December 11, 1973, and created the **American Revolution Bicentennial Administration** (ARBA), which it charged with encouraging and coordinating locally sponsored events.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Blackburn, co-designer of the modernized NASA insignia, designed the logo.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The logo consisted of a white five-point star inside a stylized star of red, white and blue.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] It was encircled by the inscription *American Revolution Bicentennial 1776–1976* in Helvetica Regular.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] An early use of the logo was on a 1971 US postage stamp.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The logo became a flag that flew at many government facilities throughout the United States and appeared on many other souvenirs and postage stamps issued by the Postal Service.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] NASA painted the logo on the Vehicle Assembly Building at the Kennedy Space Center in 1976 where it remained until 1998 when the agency replaced it with its own emblem as part of its 40th anniversary celebrations.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] In 1973, on the shores of Boston Harbor, activists and history enthusiasts recreated the Boston Tea Party.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] This reenactment later was termed as the "Boston Oil Party", and roughly 10,000 people witnessed the dumping of oil conglomerates, as well as the hanging of an effigy of President Nixon.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The official Bicentennial events began April 1, 1975, when the *American Freedom Train* launched in Wilmington, Delaware to start its 21-month, 25,388-mile (40,858 km) tour of the 48 contiguous states.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] On April 18, 1975, President Gerald Ford traveled to Boston to light a third lantern at the historic Old North Church, symbolizing America's third century.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The following day, April 19, he delivered a major address in Concord, Massachusetts at the Old North Bridge where the "shot heard round the world" was fired, commemorating the 200th anniversary of the Battles of Lexington and Concord which began the military aspect of the American Revolution.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] According to the *New York Times* "more than 2,000 spectators were on hand" as cannons were fired and a Paul Revere reenactor rode through announcing the arrival of British regulars.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] On December 31, 1975, the eve of the Bicentennial Year, Ford recorded a statement to address the American people by means of radio and television broadcasts.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Presidential Proclamation 4411 was signed as an affirmation to the Founding Fathers of the United States principles of dignity, equality, government by representation, and liberty.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] 1976 festivities included elaborate fireworks in the skies above major US cities.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] President Ford presided over the display in Washington, D.C., which was televised nationally.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Celebrations in cities and towns across the nation opened into full effect including celebrations such as Operation Sail (Op Sail), a large international fleet parade of tall-masted sailing ships gathering first in New York City on Independence Day and then in Boston about one week later.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Other large-scale events, such as reenactments, parades, and booms in commercialized commemoration, spread across the nation as the year went on.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] In addition to the presence of the 'tall ships', navies of many nations sent warships to New York harbor for an International Naval Review held the morning of July 4.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] President Ford sailed down the Hudson River into New York harbor aboard the guided missile cruiser USS *Wainwright* to review the international fleet and receive salutes from each visiting ship, ending with a salute from the Royal Navy guided-missile destroyer HMS *London*.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The review ended just above Liberty Island at around 10:30 am.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Johnny Cash served as the Grand Marshal of the US Bicentennial parade.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The event was attended by Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The royal couple made a state visit to the United States, toured the country, and attended other Bicentennial functions with President and Mrs.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Their visit aboard the British royal yacht HMY *Britannia* included stops in Philadelphia, Washington, D.C., Virginia, New York, Connecticut, and Massachusetts.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Smithsonian Institution opened a long-term exhibition in its Arts and Industries Building replicating the look and feel of the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia, including artifacts from earlier exposition.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Bicentennial Festival of American Folklife, a collaboration of the Smithsonian with thousands of national and international scholars, folk artisans, and performers, hosted programs in the western part of the National Mall five days a week for twelve weeks in the summer of 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Smithsonian also opened the new home of the National Air and Space Museum on July 1, 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] George Washington was posthumously appointed to the grade of General of the Armies of the United States by the congressional joint resolution Public Law 94-479 passed January 19, 1976, with an effective appointment date of July 4, 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] This restored Washington's position as the highest-ranking military officer in US history.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] NASA commemorated the Bicentennial by staging a science and technology exhibit housed in a series of geodesic domes in the parking lot of the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) called *Third Century America*.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] An American flag and the Bicentennial emblem were also painted on the side of the VAB; the emblem remained until 1998, when it was painted over with the NASA insignia.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] NASA planned for *Viking 1* to land on Mars on July 4, but delayed the landing to July 20, the anniversary of the Apollo 11 lunar landing.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] On the anniversary of the signing of the Constitution, NASA held the rollout ceremony of the first Space Shuttle (which NASA had planned to name *Constitution* but was, instead, named "Enterprise" in honor of its fictional namesake on the television series *Star Trek*).
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] On November 20 and 21 of 1976, participants immersed themselves in the era by donning period-accurate uniforms and equipping themselves with the tools and weaponry characteristic of that Christmas night over two centuries prior.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The reenactment unfolded as a grand spectacle, featuring a flotilla of boats navigating the icy currents of the Delaware River.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Since then, the Crossing the Delaware reenactment has occurred every year to relive and recognize this moment.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] While in Philadelphia on July 6, 1976, Queen Elizabeth II presented the Bicentennial Bell on behalf of the British people.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Disneyland and the Magic Kingdom at Walt Disney World presented *America on Parade*, an elaborate parade celebrating American history and culture, and featured the Sherman Brothers' song "The Glorious Fourth".
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The parade featured nightly fireworks and ran twice daily from June 1975 to September 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The overall theme of the entertainment of Super Bowl X, held on January 18, was to celebrate the Bicentennial.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Players on both teams, the Pittsburgh Steelers and the Dallas Cowboys, wore a special patch with the Bicentennial Logo on their jerseys; the Cowboys also added red, white, and blue striping to their helmets throughout the 1976 NFL season.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The halftime show, featuring the performance group Up with People, was entitled "200 Years and Just a Baby: A Tribute to America's Bicentennial".
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The United States Olympic Committee (USOC) initiated bids to host both the 1976 Summer and Winter Olympic Games to celebrate the Bicentennial.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Los Angeles bid for the 1976 Summer Olympics but lost to Montreal.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Denver was awarded the 1976 Winter Olympics in 1970.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Still, concern over costs led Colorado voters to reject a referendum to fund the games, and the International Olympic Committee awarded the games to Innsbruck, Austria, the host of the 1964 games.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] As a result, there was no Olympics in the United States in 1976 despite a last minute offer from Salt Lake City to host.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] However, Lake Placid would host the 1980 Winter Olympics, Los Angeles would eventually host the 1984 Summer Olympics, and Salt Lake City would also eventually host the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The 1976 Pro Bowl was an exception and was played in New Orleans, likely due to weather concerns.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Local observances included painting mailboxes and fire hydrants red, white, and blue.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] A wave of patriotism and nostalgia swept the nation, and there was a general feeling that the era of the civil rights movement, the Vietnam War, and the Watergate constitutional crisis of 1974 had finally come to an end.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] In the summer of 1976, the city of South Bend, Indiana, embarked on a unique project to commemorate the United States Bicentennial: painting its fire hydrants in vibrant colors and patriotic designs.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Over four decades later, many of South Bend's painted fire hydrants still stand as reminders of America's Bicentennial celebration.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Bell Telephone Company commissioned Stanley Meltzoff to create a cover for its 1976 directory to commemorate both the Bicentennial and the centennial of the invention of the telephone.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Based on Norman Rockwell's *The Gossips*, Meltzoff depicted America's great historic and iconic figures using the telephone.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] It became the biggest-selling directory in Bell's history.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Many national railroads and shortlines painted locomotives or rolling stock in patriotic color schemes, typically numbered 1776 or 1976, and model railroad manufacturers quickly released bicentennial locomotives, which were popular among children and adults.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Many military units marked aircraft with special designs in honor of the Bicentennial.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The New Jersey Lottery operated a special "Bicentennial Lottery" in which the winner received $1,776 per week (before taxes) for 20 years (a total of $1,847,040).
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Bicentennial Wagon Train Pilgrimage began a journey from Blaine, Washington on June 8, 1975, concluding at Valley Forge, Pennsylvania on July 4, 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The wagon train pilgrimage traced the original covered wagon trade and transportation routes across the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Conestoga wagon overland pilgrimage encompassed the Bozeman Trail, California Trail, Gila Trail, Great Wagon Road, Mormon Trail, Natchez Trace Trail, Old Post Road, Old Spanish Trail, Oregon Trail, Overland Trail, Santa Fe Trail, and Wilderness Road.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Karen Steele was the first baby born on July 4, 1976, 12 seconds after midnight, and was referred to as the "Bicentennial Baby".
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] She was featured on *The Today Show* and *Good Morning America*, and received commemorations from President Ford, New Jersey Governor Brendan Byrne, and a host of other notables.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Many commercial products, including sports, apparel, and collectibles, appeared in red, white, and blue packages in an attempt to tie them to the Bicentennial.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Liberty, a brand of Spanish olives, sold its product in glass jars that replicated the Liberty Bell at the time.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Products were only permitted to display the trademarked Bicentennial logo by paying a license fee to ARBA.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The US government also commemorated the Bicentennial by creating new designs for national currency.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The creation of the ceremonial coinage was both a way to get the American public involved in celebrating the Bicentennial and to encourage Americans to collect and purchase more Bicentennial memorabilia.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The *Bicentennial Minute* was a series of short vignettes aired on CBS from 1974 through the end of 1976 to mark the occasion.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] In the months leading up to the Bicentennial, *Schoolhouse Rock!*, a series of educational cartoon shorts airing on ABC between programs on Saturday mornings, created a sub-series called "History Rock".
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] However, the official name was "America Rock".
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The ten segments covered various aspects of American history and government.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Several of the segments, most notably "I'm Just a Bill" (discussing the legislative process) and "The Preamble" (which features a variant of the preamble of the Constitution put to music), have become some of *Schoolhouse Rock*'s most popular segments.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] In 1974, CBS aired a new animated Archie series on Saturday mornings called *The U.S. of Archie*; 16 episodes were produced and aired in reruns until September 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] For the Bicentennial celebration, Hollywood filmmaker John Huston directed a short movie—*Independence* (1976)—for the US National Park Service which continues to screen at Independence National Historical Park in Philadelphia.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The 1976 film *Rocky* cited the Bicentennial in several scenes, mostly during Apollo Creed's entering; Carl Weathers dressed first as George Washington and then as Uncle Sam.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The oversize vehicle in the 1976 film *The Big Bus* had a scene in its Bicentennial Dining Room.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Several nations gave gifts to the US as a token of friendship.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The United Kingdom loaned one of the four existing copies of Magna Carta for display in the United States Capitol.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Capitol displayed the document in a case designed by artist Louis Osman consisting of gold, stainless steel, rubies, pearls, sapphires, diamonds, and white enamel.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] This was on a base of pegmatite and Yorkshire sandstone.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The document was displayed atop a gold replica from June 3, 1976, until June 13, 1977, when it was returned.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The case and gold replica remain on display in the Capitol.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Canada, through the National Film Board of Canada, produced the book *Between Friends/Entre Amis*, a photographic essay on life along the US-Canada border.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Canada distributed the book to libraries across the US and presented special editions to President Ford and other officials.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The government of France and the Louvre assembled an exhibit of paintings in cooperation with the Detroit Institute of Arts and the Metropolitan Museum of Art that traveled to Detroit and New York City after being shown in Paris.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The exhibit, entitled *French Painting 1774–1830: The Age of Revolution*, included the work of 94 French artists from that period.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Many of the 149 works in the exhibit had never been seen outside France and included *Liberty Leading the People* by Eugène Delacroix, *Jupiter and Thetis* by Jean Auguste Dominique Ingres and a portrait of Maximilien Robespierre by Adélaïde Labille-Guiard.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Japan's government constructed and furnished the 513-seat Terrace Theatre of John F.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts in Washington.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Many of the original furnishings were removed during the theater's renovation between 2015 and 2019.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Fifty-three bonsai trees from the Nippon Bonsai Association were donated to the US National Arboretum.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] King Juan Carlos I and Queen Sofía of Spain presented sculptures of *Bernardo de Gálvez*, a hero of the American Revolutionary War period and later Viceroy of New Spain; and *Don Quixote*, Cervantes' fictional hero, on June 3, 1976, on behalf of their nation.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Gálvez sculpture is in a park at Virginia Avenue at 21st Street NW, which has been named Galvez Park.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] The Don Quixote sculpture was installed nearby on the grounds of The Kennedy Center.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] Spain's gift also included an exhibit at the National Gallery of Art of eight Goya masterpieces from the collection of *Museo del Prado*.
[src:american-community-survey/american-bicentennial] King of Norway Olav V, Prime Minister of Norway Odvar Nordli, and the Norwegian government established the Vinland National Health Sports Center in Loretto, Minnesota.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The **American Community Survey** (**ACS**) is an annual demographics survey program conducted by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] It regularly gathers information previously contained only in the long form of the decennial census, including ancestry, US citizenship status, educational attainment, income, language proficiency, migration, disability, employment, and housing characteristics.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] None of the respondents' personal information is released, and it is only used statistically in these data, which are used by many public-sector, private-sector, and not-for-profit stakeholders to allocate funding, track shifting demographics, plan for emergencies, and learn about local communities.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Sent to approximately 295,000 addresses monthly, or 3.5 million addresses annually, it is the largest household survey that the Census Bureau administers.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The American Community Survey gathers information annually in the 50 U.S. states and Washington, D.C.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Data is also collected in Puerto Rico via the **Puerto Rico Community Survey** (**PRCS**), which is part of the ACS.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] It does not gather information on the other four major U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Island areas: American Samoa, Guam, Northern Mariana Islands in the western Pacific Ocean, and the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Article I, Section II of the Constitution of the United States of 1787, adopted in 1788, requires an enumeration of the population every ten years "in such Manner as they (Congress) shall by Law direct".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] From the first United States Decennial Census three years later in 1790, congressional legislators understood that it should also collect basic demographic information beyond just the number of people in the household.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] James Madison, an American Founding Father and the fourth President of the United States, first proposed including additional questions in the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Decennial Census to "enable them to adapt the public measures to the particular circumstances of the community".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Such knowledge collected with each census, President Madison argued, "would give them an opportunity of marking the progress of the society".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The questions included in censuses since 1790 have reflected American understandings of and concerns about societal trends and the growing nation's expanded data needs.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] In the decades that followed, new questions were added to those that had previously been asked of all respondents, and all the questions were moved to the sample questionnaire form.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] As the sample form grew longer than the census form itself, it became known as the Census "long form".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Decennial Census, federal, state, and local governmental officials and some in the private sector began demanding more timely long-form-type data.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Lawmakers representing rural districts claimed they were at a data disadvantage, unable to self-fund additional surveys of their populations.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Congress explored the creation of a mid-decade census, holding hearings and even authorizing a special mid-decade census in the American Bicentennial year of 1976, but not funding it.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Efforts to obtain data on a more frequent basis began again after the 1990 U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Decennial Census when it became clear that the more burdensome long form was depressing overall census response rates and jeopardizing the accuracy of the count.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Census Bureau in the United States Department of Commerce developed and tested a new design to obtain long-form data.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Noted U.S. statistician/mathematician Leslie Kish had introduced the concept of a rolling sample (or continuous measurement) design in 1981.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] This design featured ongoing, monthly data collection aggregated every year, enabling annual data releases.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] By combining multiple years of this data, the Census Bureau could release "period" estimates to produce estimates for smaller areas.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] After a decade of testing, it launched as the American Community Survey in 2005, replacing the once-a-decade census long form.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The American Community Survey initially sampled approximately 3.5 million housing unit addresses and group quarters in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The Census Bureau selects a random sample of addresses to be included in the ACS.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Each address has about a 1-in-480 chance of being selected in a given month, and no address should be selected more than once every five years.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Data is collected by internet, mail, telephone interviews, and in-person interviews.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The questionnaire is available in English and Spanish, with assistance provided in additional languages.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Approximately one-third of those who do not respond to the survey by mail or telephone are randomly selected for in-person interviews.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] About 95 percent of households across all response modes ultimately participate in the survey.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Like the decennial census, ACS responses are confidential.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Every employee at the Census Bureau takes an oath of nondisclosure and is sworn for life to not disclose identifying information.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Violations of the nondisclosure oath are punishable by prison sentences of up to five years and/or a $250,000 fine.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Under 13 U.S.C. § 9, census responses are "immune from the legal process" and may not "be admitted as evidence or used for any purpose in any action, suit, or another judicial or administrative proceeding".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The Census Bureau aggregates individual ACS responses, also known as microdata, into estimates at many geographic summary levels.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Among these summary levels are legal and administrative entities such as states, counties, cities, and congressional districts, as well as statistical entities such as metropolitan statistical areas, tracts, block groups, and census-designated places.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Estimates for census blocks are not available from ACS.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Puerto Rico is the only US territory that is part of the ACS program.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] To balance geographic resolution, temporal frequency, statistical significance, and respondent privacy, ACS estimates released each year are aggregated from responses received in the previous calendar year or the previous five calendar years.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The Census Bureau provides guidance for data users about which data set to use when analyzing different population and geography sizes.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] From 2007 to 2013, three-year estimates were available for areas with 20,000 people or more.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] This data product was discontinued in 2015 due to budget cuts.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The last 3-year release was the 2011–2013 ACS 3-year estimates.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Over the past decade, the American Community Survey has collected and supplied all data at local levels.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] This was a large breakthrough in the survey because it allowed American citizens to more individualized data on a community level as opposed to extrapolating from data collected over a larger area.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] It has also provided unparalleled information to be more accessible for local government planning and financing.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Many conclusions for local data are averaged from various information across the area, but it is not always an adequate representation.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] ACS estimates are available via several online data tools.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Census website (AFF) is the primary tool for disseminating ACS data, allowing users to drill down to specific tables and geographies (starting with 2013 estimates, AFF also includes block group data).
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] A selection of the most popular tables is shown in QuickFacts.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Other tools include OnTheMap for Emergency Management, Census Business Builder and My Congressional District.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] My Tribal Area featuring 5-year estimates for federally recognized tribes, launched in 2017.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The Summary File is the most detailed data source and is available as a series of downloadable text files or through an application programming interface (API) for software developers.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Custom cross-tabulations of ACS questions can be made using the Public Use Microdata Sample (PUMS), freely accessible through the Census Bureau website and the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] PUMS data contain responses to every question from a sample of respondents.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] To protect respondent privacy, PUMS data are anonymized and only available down to areas containing 100,000 people or more known as Public Use Microdata Areas (PUMAs).
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The analysis of all ACS microdata without the sampling and anonymization in PUMS is restricted to qualified researchers at secure Federal Statistical Research Data Centers (FSRDCs).
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The Census Bureau conducts research and evaluation projects, including survey methodology research, important for the improvement of the ACS.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The ACS data is used by researchers to examine societal changes, study data quality, and conduct methodological research.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] American Community Survey data provides important information that cannot be found elsewhere.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The federal government, as well as various businesses, researchers, and local governments, use ACS data for planning and decision-making purposes.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] ACS data are used by public and business decision-makers to more clearly identify issues and opportunities and more effectively allocate scarce resources to address them.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] In Fiscal Year 2008, 184 federal domestic assistance programs used ACS-related datasets to help guide the distribution of $416 billion, 29 percent of all federal assistance.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The American Community Survey is authorized by 13 U.S.C. § 141 and 13 U.S.C. § 193.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Federal courts have held that the long form is constitutional.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] District Court for the Southern District of Texas ruled that the 2000 U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Decennial Census and its questions did not violate the Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution or any other constitutional provisions that were alleged in the federal lawsuit initiated by the plaintiffs.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The federal district court said responses to census questions are not a violation of an American citizen's right to privacy or free speech.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] District Court's decision in Texas was later affirmed by the higher United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit on appeal, and the Supreme Court of the United States denied the petition for a writ of certiorari.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Several other courts, including the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Supreme Court, have held through the years that the Census and the questions in the Census are authorized by both the Constitution and Congressional statute.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] In 2002, the General Accounting Office confirmed that the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Census Bureau has the authority to conduct the survey and "require responses from the public".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] All individual American Community Survey responses are kept private and are used (along with other ACS responses) to create estimates of demographic characteristics for various geographies.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Because of data swapping techniques to ensure confidentiality, it is impossible to figure out how individual people responded based on data from published ACS estimates.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Opponents of the American Community Survey disagree with the court's findings about its constitutionality, contending that the survey asks for more information and at a higher frequency than the simple enumeration authorized and required by Article 1, Section 2 of the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Despite the Government Accountability Office's conclusion that the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Census Bureau has the authority to the survey under 13 U.S.C. § 141 and 13 U.S.C. § 193, several US representatives have challenged the ACS as unauthorized by the Census Act and a violation of the Right to Financial Privacy Act.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Representative (congressman) Ron Paul of Texas, who opposes ACS, said that the founding fathers of the United States "never authorized the federal government to continuously survey the American people".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Those who decline to complete the survey may receive visits to their homes from Census Bureau personnel.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Because it is a mandatory survey, it is governed by federal laws that could impose a fine of as much as $5,000 on those who flagrantly refuse to participate.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] To date, no person has been prosecuted for refusing to answer the ACS.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Kenneth Prewitt, the former director of the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Census Bureau, said in March 2000 that the United States Department of Commerce is "not an enforcement agency" and that the parallel United States Department of Justice in the presidential cabinet would be responsible for prosecuting violations, adding that "we don't recommend that".
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The Census Bureau prefers to gain cooperation by convincing respondents of the importance of participation while acknowledging that the mandate improves response rates (and thus accuracy) and lowers the annual cost of survey administration by more than $90 million.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] In 2014, the Census Project, a collaboration of pro-census business and industry associations, gathered signatures from 96 national and local organizations urging the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] House of Representatives Committee on Oversight and Government Reform to reject a proposal to make the American Community Survey voluntary.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] Chamber of Commerce, the National Association of Realtors, and the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The letter cited results from a congressionally mandated test of a voluntary ACS that found that mail response rates would drop "dramatically," by more than 20 percentage points.
[src:american-community-survey/american-community-survey] The resulting loss in quality and reliability would essentially eliminate data for 41 percent of US counties, small cities, towns and villages, many school districts, neighborhoods, remote areas, and American Indian reservations.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa consists of the eastern part of the Samoan archipelago – the inhabited volcanic islands of Tutuila, Aunuʻu, Ofu, Olosega and Taʻū and the uninhabited Rose Atoll – as well as Swains Island, a remote coral atoll in the Tokelau volcanic island group.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The total land area is 77 square miles (199 km2), slightly larger than Washington, D.C.; including its territorial waters, the total area is 117,500 square miles (304,000 km2), about the size of New Zealand.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa has a tropical climate, with 90 percent of its land covered by rainforests.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] As of 2024, the population is approximately 47,400 and concentrated on Tutuila, which hosts the capital and largest settlement, Pago Pago.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The vast majority of residents are indigenous ethnic Samoans, most of whom are fluent in the official languages, Samoan and English.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Inhabited by Polynesians since prehistoric times, American Samoa was first contacted by Europeans in the 18th century.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The islands attracted missionaries, explorers, and mariners, particularly to the highly protected natural harbor of Pago Pago.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The United States took possession of American Samoa in the late 19th century, developing it into a major naval outpost; the territory's strategic value was reinforced by the Second World War and subsequent Cold War.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 1967, American Samoa became self-governing with the adoption of a constitution; its local government is republican in form, with separate executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] It remains officially unorganized and is thus directly administered by the federal government.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Due to the territory's strategic location, the U.S. military has a significant presence and plays a major role in its economy and society.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The territory is noted for having the highest rate of military enlistment of any U.S. state or territory; as of 2021, the local U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Army recruiting station in Pago Pago ranked first in recruitment.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Tuna products are the main exports, with the U.S. proper serving as the largest trading partner.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Tourism is a nascent but underdeveloped sector, owing in part to the territory's relative geographic isolation, which also accounts for its high rate of poverty and emigration.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Since the Deeds of Cession were signed in 1900 and 1904, Samoans have avoided further integration into the U.S. system.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 1949, the Department of the Interior moved to incorporate American Samoa through an Organic Act.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Afraid that incorporation might undermine the Samoan culture and traditional land ownership, Samoan matai intervened and Congress halted incorporation.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Instead, Samoa created its own government, the Samoan Fono, based on indigenous systems of governance.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Since then, Samoans have declined to establish a federal district court and refused birthright citizenship; Samoa remains the only U.S. territory with its own immigration system.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Many consider residents of American Samoa to be politically disenfranchised, with no voting representation in the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Congress, though American Samoa itself has a democratic system of governance.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] However, many Samoans have prioritized indigenous culture and government over integration into the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is the only permanently inhabited territory of the United States in which citizenship is not granted at birth, and people born there are considered "non-citizen nationals" with limited rights.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] A primary reason that Samoans do not have birthright citizenship is that it is opposed by many Samoans, as evidenced by the unanimous resolution of the Samoan Fono in 2021 against birthright citizenship, and multiple statements and actions by government officials over the decades.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The elected representatives of American Samoan people unanimously fear that birthright citizenship would complicate the territory's political structure and lead to the erosion of indigenous governance, collective ownership of indigenous lands, and use of the Samoan language.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The origin of the name "Samoa" means "holy center", taken from a compound of the Samoan *sa* ("sacred") and *moa* ("center").
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The name is alternatively derived from a local chieftain named Samoa or an indigenous word meaning "place of the moa", a now-extinct bird, though the bird was known only from New Zealand.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Although the sovereign state of Samoa changed its name from Western Samoa in 1997, the territory is also sometimes referred to as *Eastern Samoa* to distinguish it from its neighbor.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Traditional oral literature of Samoa and Manuʻa talks of a widespread Polynesian network or confederacy (or "empire") that was prehistorically ruled by the successive Tui Manuʻa dynasties.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Manuan genealogies and religious oral literature also suggest that the Tui Manuʻa had long been one of the most prestigious and powerful paramounts of Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Oral history suggests that the Tui Manuʻa kings governed a confederacy of far-flung islands which included Tutuila, as well as smaller western Pacific chiefdoms and Polynesian outliers such as Uvea, Futuna, Tokelau, Tuvalu and bigger islands like the Samoa in the North.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Contact with Europeans began in the early 18th century.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Dutchman Jacob Roggeveen was the first known European to sight the Samoan Islands in 1722, calling them the "Baumann Islands" after one of his captains.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The next explorer to visit the islands was Louis-Antoine de Bougainville, who named them the "Îles des Navigateurs" in 1768.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] British explorer James Cook recorded the island names in 1773, but never visited.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The 1789 visit by Lapérouse was ended by an attack, on Tutuila island where Lapérouse's men were trying to obtain water.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] His second in command Capt. de Langle, and scientist Robert de Lamanon and several of his crew were surrounded by over a thousand Samoans and killed.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] La Pérouse named the island "Massacre Island", and the bay near Aasu is still called Massacre Bay.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] HMS *Pandora*, under the command of Admiral Edward Edwards (Royal Navy officer), visited the island in 1791 during its search for the H.M.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Mission work in the Samoas had begun in late 1830 when John Williams of the London Missionary Society arrived from the Cook Islands and Tahiti.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] By the late nineteenth century, French, British, German, and American vessels routinely stopped at Samoa, as they valued Pago Pago Harbor as a refueling station for coal-fired shipping and whaling.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The United States Exploring Expedition visited the islands in 1839.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Meade of the USS *Narragansett* sailed from Hawai'i to Pago Pago to explore the establishment of a U.S. naval station.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Peirce, the U.S. minister to Hawai'i, he was also tasked with negotiating a treaty that would secure American interests in Sāmoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The *Narragansett* reached Pago Pago on February 14, and Meade informed High Chief Mauga of his intention to lease land for a naval base.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Mauga granted the United States exclusive rights to build and maintain such a station in exchange for “the friendship and protection of the great government of the United States.” During his stay, Meade also arranged commercial port regulations for Pago Pago with Mauga.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In March 1889, an Imperial German naval force entered a village in Samoa, and in doing so destroyed some American property.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Three American warships then entered the Apia harbor and prepared to engage the three German warships found there.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Before any shots were fired, a typhoon wrecked both the American and German ships.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] A compulsory armistice was then called because of the lack of any warships.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Forerunners to the Tripartite Convention of 1899 were the Washington Conference of 1887, the Treaty of Berlin of 1889 and the Anglo-German Agreement on Samoa of 1899.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The following year, the U.S. formally annexed its portion, a smaller group of eastern islands, one of which contains the noted harbor of Pago Pago.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] After the United States Navy took possession of eastern Samoa for the United States government, the existing coaling station at Pago Pago Bay was expanded into a full naval station, known as United States Naval Station Tutuila and commanded by a commandant.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Navy secured a Deed of Cession of Tutuila in 1900 and a Deed of Cession of Manuʻa in 1904 on behalf of the U.S. government.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The last sovereign of Manuʻa, the Tui Manuʻa Elisala, signed a Deed of Cession of Manuʻa following a series of U.S. naval trials, known as the "Trial of the Ipu", in Pago Pago, Taʻu, and aboard a Pacific Squadron gunboat.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Naval Station Tutuila, which was composed of Tutuila, Aunuʻu and Manuʻa, was officially renamed American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] People of Manuʻa had been unhappy since they were left out of the name "Naval Station Tutuila".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In May 1911, Governor William Michael Crose authored a letter to the Secretary of the Navy conveying the sentiments of Manuʻa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The department responded that the people should choose a name for their new territory.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The traditional leaders chose "American Samoa", and, on July 7, 1911, the solicitor general of the Navy authorized the governor to proclaim it as the name for the new territory.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 1918, during the final stages of World War I, the Great Influenza epidemic had taken its toll, spreading rapidly from country to country.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The result of Poyer's quick actions earned him the Navy Cross from the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] With this distinction, American Samoans regarded Poyer as their hero for what he had done to prevent the deadly disease.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The neighboring New Zealand territory at the time, Western Samoa, suffered the most of all Pacific islands, with 90% of the population infected; 30% of adult men, 22% of adult women and 10% of children died.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Poyer offered assistance to help his New Zealand counterparts but was refused by the administrator of Western Samoa, Robert Logan, who became outraged after witnessing the number of quarantine ships surrounding American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Angered by this, Logan cut off communications with his American counterparts.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] After World War I, during the time of the Mau movement in Western Samoa (then a League of Nations mandate governed by New Zealand), there was a corresponding American Samoa Mau movement led by Samuelu Ripley, a World War I veteran who was from Leone village, Tutuila.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] After meetings on the United States mainland, he was prevented from disembarking from the ship that brought him home to American Samoa and was not allowed to return because the American Samoa Mau movement was suppressed by the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Congress sent a committee to investigate the status of American Samoa, led by Americans who had a part in the overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Swains Island, which had been included in the list of guano islands appertaining to the United States and bonded under the Guano Islands Act, was annexed in 1925 by Pub.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] 68–75, following the dissolution of the Gilbert and Ellice Islands Protectorate by the United Kingdom.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Marines stationed in Samoa outnumbered the local population and had a huge cultural influence.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Young Samoan men from age 14 and above were combat-trained by U.S. military personnel.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Samoans served in various capacities during World War II, including as combatants, medical personnel, code personnel, and ship repairmen.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Department of Interior–sponsored attempt to incorporate American Samoa, was introduced in Congress.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] It was ultimately defeated, primarily through the efforts of Samoan chiefs, led by Tuiasosopo Mariota.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The efforts of these chiefs led to the creation of a territorial legislature, the American Samoa Fono, which meets in the village of Fagatogo.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 1950 the Department of the Interior began to administer American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Navy-appointed governor was replaced by Peter Tali Coleman, who was locally elected.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Although technically considered "unorganized" since the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Congress has not passed an Organic Act for the territory, American Samoa is self-governing under a constitution that became effective on July 1, 1967.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Territory of American Samoa is on the United Nations list of non-self-governing territories, a listing which is disputed by the territorial government officials, who do consider themselves to be self-governing.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa and Pago Pago International Airport had historic significance with the Apollo Program.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The astronaut crews of Apollo 10, 12, 13, 14, and 17 were retrieved a few hundred miles from Pago Pago and transported by helicopter to the airport prior to being flown to Honolulu on C-141 Starlifter military aircraft.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] While the two Samoas share language and ethnicity, their cultures have recently followed different paths, with American Samoans often emigrating to Hawaiʻi and the U.S. mainland and adopting many U.S. customs, such as the playing of American football and baseball.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Samoans have tended to emigrate instead to New Zealand, whose influence has made the sports of rugby and cricket more popular in the western Samoan islands.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Travel writer Paul Theroux noted that there were marked differences between the societies in Samoa and American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On August 13, 1999, the United Nations granted American Samoa "observer seat" status.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Six days later, American Samoa officially recognized both Samoan and English as its official languages.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 2001 and 2003, the United States unsuccessfully sought to have American Samoa removed from the United Nations' decolonization list, arguing that the territory should not be considered a colony.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoans have a high rate of service in the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Because of economic hardship, military service has been seen as an opportunity in American Samoa and other U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The federal Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2007 started gradual adjustments to the territorial minimum wage to bring it up to the level for U.S. states.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On December 13, 1784, French navigator Jean-François de Galaup, comte de Lapérouse landed two exploration parties on Tutuila's north shore: one from the ship *Boussole* at Fagasā, and the other from *L'Astrolabe* at Aʻasu.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] One of the cooks, David, died of "scorbutic dropsy".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] This incident gave Samoa a reputation for savagery that kept Europeans away until the arrival of the first Christian missionaries four decades later.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On December 12, at Aʻasu Bay, Lapérouse ordered his gunners to fire one cannonball amid the attackers who had killed his men the day before and were now returning to launch another attack.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On December 19, 1912, English writer William Somerset Maugham arrived in Pago Pago, allegedly accompanied by a missionary and Miss Sadie Thompson.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] His visit inspired his short story "Rain" which later became plays and three major motion pictures.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The building still stands where Maugham stayed and has been renamed the Sadie Thompson Building.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Today, it is a prominent restaurant and inn.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On November 2, 1921, American Samoa's 13th naval governor, Commander Warren Jay Terhune, died by suicide with a pistol in the bathroom of the government mansion, overlooking the entrance to Pago Pago Harbor.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] His body was discovered by Government House's cook, SDI First Class Felisiano Debid Ahchica, USN.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] His ghost is rumored to walk about the grounds at night.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On August 17, 1924, Margaret Mead arrived in American Samoa aboard the SS *Sonoma* to begin fieldwork for her doctoral dissertation in anthropology at Columbia University, where she was a student of Professor Franz Boas.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Her work *Coming of Age in Samoa* was published in 1928, at the time becoming the most widely read book in the field of anthropology.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The book has sparked years of ongoing and intense debate and controversy.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Mead returned to American Samoa in 1971 for the dedication of the Jean P.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 1938, the noted aviator Ed Musick and his crew died on the Pan American World Airways S-42 *Samoan Clipper* over Pago Pago, while on a survey flight to Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Sometime after takeoff, the aircraft experienced trouble, and Musick turned it back toward Pago Pago.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] While the crew dumped fuel in preparation for an emergency landing, an explosion occurred that tore the aircraft apart.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On November 24, 1939, American Samoa's last execution to date was carried out.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] A man named Imoa of Fagatogo was convicted of stabbing a person named Sella to death and was hanged in the Customs House.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The popular Samoan song "Faʻafofoga Samoa" is based on this, said to be the final words of Imoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On January 13, 1942, at 2:26 a.m., a Japanese submarine surfaced off Tutuila between Southworth Point and Fagasa Bay and fired about 15 shells from its 5.5-inch deck gun at the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Naval Station Tutuila over the next 10 minutes.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The first shell struck the rear of Frank Shimasaki's store, ironically owned by one of Tutuila's few Japanese residents.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Shimasaki had been interned as an enemy alien.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The next shell caused slight damage to the naval dispensary, the third landed on the lawn behind the naval quarters known as "Centipede Row," and the fourth struck the stone seawall outside the customs house.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The other rounds fell harmlessly into the harbor.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] As one writer described it, "The fire was not returned, notwithstanding the eagerness of the Samoan Marines to test their skill against the enemy ...
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] No American or Samoan Marines were wounded." Commander Edwin B.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Robinson was bicycling behind Centipede Row and was wounded in the knee by a piece of shrapnel, and "a member of the colorful native Fita Fita Guard" received minor injuries; they were the only casualties.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On August 24, 1943, First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt visited American Samoa and inspected the Fita Fita Guard and Band and the First Samoan Battalion of U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The fact that First Lady reviewed the troops led to further assurance that Tutuila Island was considered safe.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Her presence underscored that World War II had passed by American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] While the Fita Fita band played, Eleanor Roosevelt inspected the guard.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On October 18, 1966, President Lyndon Baines Johnson and First Lady Lady Bird Johnson visited American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Johnson dedicated the "Manulele Tausala" ("Lady Bird") Elementary School in Nuʻuuli, which was named after her.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Johnson is the only US president to have visited American Samoa, while Mrs.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Johnson was the second First Lady, preceded by Eleanor Roosevelt in 1943.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The territory's only hospital was renamed the LBJ Tropical Medical Center in honor of President Johnson.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, American Samoa played a pivotal role in five of the Apollo Program missions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The astronauts landed several hundred miles from Pago and were transported to the islands en route back to the mainland.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] President Richard Nixon gave three Moon rocks to the American Samoan government, which are currently on display in the Jean P.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Haydon Museum along with a flag carried to the Moon on one of the missions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In November 1970, Pope Paul VI visited American Samoa in a brief but lavish greeting.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On January 30, 1974, Pan Am Flight 806 from Auckland, New Zealand, crashed at Pago Pago International Airport at 10:41 pm, with 91 passengers aboard.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] 86 people were killed, including Captain Leroy A.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Four of the five surviving passengers were seriously injured, with the other only slightly injured.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The airliner was destroyed by the impact and succeeding fire.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The crash was attributed to poor visibility, pilot error, or wind shear since a violent storm was raging at the time.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In January 2014, filmmaker Paul Crompton visited the territory to interview local residents for a documentary film about the 1974 crash.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] As part of the Flag Day celebrations on April 17, 1980, a U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Navy P-3 Orion patrol plane from Patrol Squadron 50 took off with six skydivers from the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Army's Hawaii-based Tropic Lightning Parachute Club.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The airplane contacted the Solo Ridge-Mount Alava aerial tramway cable across Pago Pago harbor, which sheared off its vertical stabilizer.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The aircraft crashed, demolishing a wing of the Rainmaker Hotel and killing all six crew members and one civilian.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The six skydivers had already left the aircraft during a demonstration jump.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On November 1, 1988, President Ronald Reagan signed a bill which created American Samoa National Park.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On July 22, 2010, Detective Lieutenant Lusila Brown was fatally shot outside the temporary High Court building in Fagatogo.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] It was the first time in more than 15 years that a police officer was killed in the line of duty.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The last was Sa Fuimaono, who drowned after saving a teenager from rough seas.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On November 8, 2010, United States Secretary of State and former First Lady Hillary Clinton made a refueling stopover at the Pago Pago International Airport.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] She was greeted by government dignitaries and presented with gifts and a traditional kava ceremony.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Mike Pence was the third sitting U.S. vice president to visit American Samoa (after Dan Quayle and Joe Biden) when he made a stopover in Pago Pago in April 2017.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] He addressed 200 soldiers here during his refueling stop.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Secretary of State Rex Tillerson visited town on June 3, 2017.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On September 28, 2009, at 17:48:11 UTC, an 8.1 magnitude earthquake struck 120 miles (190 km) off the coast of American Samoa, followed by smaller aftershocks.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The quake occurred on the outer rise of the Kermadec-Tonga Subduction Zone.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] This is part of the Pacific Ring of Fire, where tectonic plates in the Earth's lithosphere meet, and earthquakes and volcanic activity are common.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The quake struck 11.2 miles (18.0 km) below the ocean floor and generated an onsetting tsunami that killed more than 170 people in the Samoa Islands and Tonga.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Four waves with heights from 15 feet (4.6 m) to 20 feet (6.1 m) high were reported to have reached up to one mile (1.6 km) inland on the island of Tutuila.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Defense Logistics Agency worked with the Federal Emergency Management Agency to provide 16 ft × 16 ft (4.9 m × 4.9 m) humanitarian tents to the devastated areas of American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is classified in U.S. law as an unincorporated territory; the Ratification Act of 1929 vested all civil, judicial, and military powers in the President of the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 1951, with Executive Order 10264, President Harry Truman delegated that authority to the Secretary of the Interior.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On June 21, 1963 Paramount Chief Tuli Leʻiato of Fagaʻitua was sworn in and installed as the first Secretary of Samoan Affairs by Governor H.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On June 2, 1967, Interior Secretary Stewart Udall promulgated the Revised Constitution of American Samoa, which took effect on July 1, 1967.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Governor of American Samoa is the head of government, and, along with the Lieutenant Governor of American Samoa, is elected on the same ticket by popular vote for a four-year term.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The governor's office is located in Utulei.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Since American Samoa is a U.S. territory, the President of the United States serves as the head of state but does not play a direct role in government.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Secretary of the Interior oversees the government, retaining the power to approve constitutional amendments, overrides the governor's vetoes, and nomination of justices.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The legislative power is vested in the American Samoa Fono, which has two chambers.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The House of Representatives has 21 members serving two-year terms, being 20 representatives popularly elected from various districts and one delegate from Swains Island elected in a public meeting.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Senate has 18 members, elected for four-year terms by and from the chiefs of the islands.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The judiciary of American Samoa is composed of the High Court of American Samoa, a District Court, and village courts.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The High Court and District Court are located in Fagatogo, near the Fono.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The High Court is led by a Chief Justice and an Associate Justice, appointed by the Secretary of the Interior.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Other judges are appointed by the governor upon the recommendation of the Chief Justice and confirmed by the Senate.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is an unincorporated and unorganized territory of the United States, administered by the Office of Insular Affairs, U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa's constitution was ratified in 1966 and came into effect in 1967.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] However, despite being de jure unorganized (as no Organic Act for it has been adopted by the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Congress, instead leaving power vested in the U.S. president), American Samoa is de facto organized, with its politics taking place in the framework of a presidential representative democratic dependency (whereby an elected Governor is head of government) and of a pluriform multi-party system.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Executive power is exercised by the governor.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Legislative power is vested in the two chambers of the legislature.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The American political parties (Republican and Democratic) exist in American Samoa, but few politicians are aligned with the parties.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] There is also the traditional village politics of the Samoa Islands, the "faʻamatai" and the "faʻa Sāmoa", which continues in American Samoa and independent Samoa, and which interacts across these current boundaries.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The faʻa Sāmoa is the language and customs, and the faʻamatai are the protocols of the "fono" (council) and the chief system.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The faʻamatai and the fono take place at all levels of the Samoan body politic, from the family to the village, to the region, to national matters.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The ʻaiga is the family unit of Samoan society, which differs from the Western sense of a family in that it consists of an "extended family" based on the culture's communal socio-political organization.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The matai (chiefs) are elected by consensus within the fono of the extended family and village(s) concerned.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The matai and the fono, which are themselves made of matai, decide on the distribution of family exchanges and tenancy of communal lands.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The majority of lands in American Samoa and independent Samoa are communal.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] A matai can represent a small family group or a great extended family that reaches across islands and to both American Samoa and independent Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 2010, voters rejected a package of amendments to the territorial constitution, which would have, among other things, allowed U.S. citizens to be legislators only if they had Samoan ancestry.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 2012, both the Governor and American Samoa's delegate to the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Congress Eni Faleomavaega called for the populace to consider a move toward autonomy if not independence, with a mixed response.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] According to the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA), the people born in American Samoa – including those born on Swains Island – are "nationals but not citizens of the United States at birth".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] If a child is born on any of these islands to any U.S. citizen, then that child is considered a national and a citizen of the United States at birth.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] All U.S. nationals have statutory rights to reside in all parts of the United States, and may apply for citizenship by naturalization after three months of residency by paying a fee, passing a test in English and civics, and taking an oath of allegiance to the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] All U.S. nationals also have the right to work in the United States, except in certain government jobs that specifically require U.S. citizenship.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The question of whether American Samoans should be granted citizenship is controversial in American Samoa, and the government of American Samoa is currently opposed to it.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Those against citizenship worry that it would lead to federal judges overturning American Samoa's unique political system and land ownership customs, in which one must be at least 50% of Samoan ancestry to acquire land and land ownership is controlled by local families and *matai*.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Those in favor of citizenship claim the law discriminates against them unfairly, restricting their voting rights and their ability to serve in many public sector professions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 2012, a group of American Samoans sued the federal government seeking recognition of birthright citizenship for American Samoans in the case *Tuaua v.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In an *amicus curiae* brief filed in federal court, American Samoan Congressman Faleomavaega supported the legal interpretation that the Citizenship Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment does not extend birthright citizenship to United States nationals born in unincorporated territories.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia affirmed that Fourteenth Amendment citizenship guarantees did not apply to persons born in unincorporated territories and a year later the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Supreme Court declined to review the lower court's decision.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] On July 20, 2021, the Legislature of American Samoa unanimously passed a resolution in support of the 10th Circuit Court's decision to reverse.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] As U.S. nationals, American Samoans can vote in local elections in the territory; however, if they live in other parts of the United States, they are not allowed to vote in federal, state or the vast majority of local elections unless they become U.S. citizens.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The only federal office American Samoans elect directly is a non-voting delegate to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Since the delegate's office was created in 1978, three people have held the seat: Democrat Fofō Iosefa Fiti Sunia (1981–1988); Democrat Eni Faleomavaega (1989–2015); and Republican Aumua Amata Radewagen (2015–).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoans also participate in partisan presidential primaries, as well as send delegates to the Democratic and Republican National Conventions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Unique among U.S. territories, American Samoa has its own immigration law, separate from the laws that apply in other parts of the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] U.S. nationals may freely reside in American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoan government, via its Immigration Office, controls the migration of foreign nationals to the islands.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Special application forms exist for migration to American Samoa based on family or employment sponsorship.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Unlike all other permanently inhabited U.S. jurisdictions (states, District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Virgin Islands, Guam and Northern Mariana Islands), American Samoa is not considered a U.S. state for the purposes of the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] As a result, there is no path for immigrants to American Samoa to apply for U.S. citizenship, or U.S. nationality at all, without permanent residence in another U.S. jurisdiction.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In addition, foreign nationals who do have lawful permanent residence in the United States may be considered to have abandoned it if they have moved to live in American Samoa, and time spent there does not count in the required period of U.S. presence for naturalization.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] U.S. nationals without U.S. citizenship (the status of most American Samoans) have the right to reside in all parts of the United States without immigration restrictions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] They also have the same rights as lawful permanent residents to sponsor foreign family members to immigrate to the United States (they may sponsor spouses and unmarried children), but not the same rights as U.S. citizens (who may also sponsor parents, married children, and siblings).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Under American Samoan law, land ownership is subject to racial restrictions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Since 1900, there have been three main categories of land ownership: native, individual, and freehold.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Native land, which makes up over 90% of all land in the territory, is land under the communal ownership of an ʻaiga, as opposed to the private ownership of an individual.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Freehold land, which makes up only about 2% of the total, is land which was granted to foreigners before the U.S. took possession of the territory in 1900 and whose owners have not chosen to revert to native or individual land status.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoa Code (Annotated) prohibits the transfer of ownership (whether by sale or otherwise) of any land other than freehold land to any person who has less than one-half native Samoan blood, which in this context includes both American and Western Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In addition, it is prohibited to transfer ownership of any native (communal) land to any person who is not a full-blooded native Samoan: this includes any person who has any non-native blood whatsoever, even if they are more than one-half native Samoan.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] 10, 14 (1980), the Appellate Division of the High Court of American Samoa held that while these laws created a classification based on race, they did not violate the guarantees of equal protection and due process contained in the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Constitution and the Revised American Samoan Constitution.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Embassy in Samoa notes that: "In July 1997 the Constitution was amended to change the country's name from Western Samoa to Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Samoa had been known simply as Samoa in the United Nations since joining the organization in 1976.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The neighboring U.S. territory of American Samoa protested the move, feeling that the change diminished its own Samoan identity.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is administratively divided into three districts – Western, Eastern and Manuʻa – and two "unorganized" atolls, Swains Island and the uninhabited Rose Atoll.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The districts are subdivided into counties and villages.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Pago Pago, often cited as the capital of American Samoa, is one of the largest villages and is located on the central part of Tutuila island in Maʻoputasi County.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa, located within the geographical region of Oceania, is one of only two possessions of the United States in the Southern Hemisphere, the other being Jarvis Island.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Its total land area is 76.1 square miles (197.1 km2) – slightly larger than Washington, D.C. – consisting of five rugged, volcanic islands and two coral atolls.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The five volcanic islands are Tutuila, Aunuʻu, Ofu, Olosega, and Taʻū.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The coral atolls are Swains and Rose Atoll.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Of the seven islands, Rose Atoll is the only uninhabited one; it is a Marine National Monument.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is the southernmost reach of the United States at fourteen degrees below the equator.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Due to its positioning in the South Pacific Ocean, it is frequently hit by tropical cyclones between November and April.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Rose Atoll is the easternmost point of the territory.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa's Rose Atoll is the southernmost point of the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is home to the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Mount Pioa, nicknamed the Rainmaker, is 1,718 ft (524 m).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is also home to some of the world's highest sea cliffs at 3,000 ft (910 m).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Vailuluʻu seamount, an active submerged volcano, lies 28 miles (45 km) east of Taʻū in American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] It was discovered in 1975 and has since been studied by an international team of scientists, contributing towards understanding of the Earth's fundamental processes.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Growing inside the summit crater of Vailuluʻu is an active underwater volcanic cone, named after Samoa's goddess of war, Nafanua.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In American Samoa forest cover is around 86% of the total land area, equivalent to 17,130 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 18,070 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 17,130 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 0 hectares (ha).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 1% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 15% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] For the year 2015, 0% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 100% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa lies within two terrestrial ecoregions: Samoan tropical moist forests and Western Polynesian tropical moist forests.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa has a tropical climate all year round with two distinct seasons, the wet and dry season.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The wet season is usually between December and March and the dry season is from April through to September with the average daily temperature around 81–83 °F (27–28 °C) all year round.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The climate is warm, tropical, and humid, averaging around 80 °F or 26.7 °C, with a variation of about 15 °F or 8 °C during the year.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The southern hemisphere winter, from June to September, is the coolest time of the year.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The summer months of December to March bring hotter temperatures, while the months from April to November are considered the "dry" season.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Throughout the year, however, rain follows clouds blown in by the trade winds that rise from the east almost daily.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The mountains of the Pago Pago area, standing over Pago Pago Harbor, catch these clouds, bringing an average of 200 inches or 5,100 millimeters of rainfall per year.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Climate change in American Samoa encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide, in the U.S. territory of American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoa Environmental Protection Agency (ASEPA) notes that the territory "has a fragile ecosystem" which is "directly and immediately impacted by global climate change".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] The Human Rights Measurement Initiative finds that the climate crisis has worsened human rights conditions in American Samoa slightly (2.3 out of 6).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p01] Human rights experts provided that the climate crisis has affected shores, fishers and resource availability, and that only a small group of people are able to connect the climate crisis with existing human rights conditions.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The economic health of American Samoa reflects the trends in other populated U.S. territories, which are in turn dependent on federal appropriations.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Federal dollars enter the economy through congressional appropriations, categorical grants, Social Security payments, and payments to Samoans retired from the military.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Tuna canning is the backbone of the American Samoa economy.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Cannery employment and local auxiliary businesses provide additional revenues for the territorial government.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In the mid-1960s, efforts began to develop a tourism industry in American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Efforts were delayed due to issues with inconsistent airline service, insufficient high-quality accommodations, and the lack of well-trained workers in the hospitality and tourism industries.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Agriculture and fishing still provide sustenance for local families.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Employment on the island falls into three relatively equal-sized categories of approximately 5,000 workers each: the public sector, the single remaining tuna cannery, and the rest of the private sector.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] There are only a few federal employees in American Samoa and a few active duty military personnel, except members of the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Coast Guard, military recruiters, and some Full-Time Support staff at the Pele Army Reserve unit that maintains the facility and provides cadre, training, and logistics support.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The Pele US Army Reserve Center is in Tafuna, and a U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Army and United States Marine Corps recruiting station is in Nuʻuuli.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The overwhelming majority of public sector employees work for the American Samoa territorial government.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] One tuna cannery is StarKist, which exports several hundred million dollars' worth of canned tuna to the United States each year.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In early 2007, the Samoan economy was highlighted in the Congress at the request of Eni Faleomavaega, the Samoan delegate to the United States House of Representatives, as it was not mentioned in the minimum wage bill.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] It was given no exemption from the coming increases, which he protested as unfair to the Samoan economy.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] House Speaker Nancy Pelosi initially granted his request for an exemption, but backed down after being accused of serving special interests, since tuna packing company Chicken of the Sea was based in her district.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Samoa Packing, a Chicken of the Sea subsidiary closed in 2009, citing both minimum wage increases and increasing foreign competition, with the latter as the "main reason".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Minimum wage in Samoa has been the topic of much debate, with the Samoan government and Chamber of Commerce strongly opposed, while businesses and workers hold nuanced views.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] From 2002 to 2007, real GDP of American Samoa increased at an average annual rate of 0.4 percent.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The annual growth rates of real GDP ranged from −2.9 percent to +2.1 percent.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The volatility in the growth rates of real GDP was primarily accounted for by changes in the exports of canned tuna.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The tuna canning industry was the largest private employer in American Samoa during this period.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In 2017, GDP in American Samoa decreased by 5.8%, but in 2018 it increased by 2.2%.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] From 2002 to 2007, the population of American Samoa increased at an average annual rate of 2.3 percent, and real GDP per capita decreased at an average annual rate of 1.9 percent.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Agricultural production covers for domestic needs and only a small share of fruits and vegetables are exported.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] According to figures as of 2013, the ratio between import and export is almost balanced.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Many residents rely on transfer payments from relatives living on the mainland or from federal subsidies.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The unemployment rate was 29.8% in 2005 but improved to 23.8% as of 2010.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In 2020, American Samoa's GDP was $709 million.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938 has contained special provisions for American Samoa since its inception, citing its limited economy.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] American Samoan wages are based on the recommendations of a Special Industry Committee meeting bi-annually.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Originally, the act contained provisions for other territories, provisions which were phased out as those territories developed more diverse economies.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In 2007, the Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2007 was passed, increasing the minimum wage in American Samoa by 50¢ per hour in 2007 and another 50¢ per hour each year thereafter until the minimum wage in American Samoa equals the federal minimum wage of $7.25 per hour in the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In response to the minimum wage increase, the Chicken of the Sea tuna canning plant was shut down in 2009, and 2,041 employees were laid off in the process.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The other major tuna canning plant in American Samoa is StarKist, which began laying off workers in August 2010, with plans to lay off a total of 800 workers due to the minimum wage increases and other rising operation costs.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Governor Togiola Tulafono suggested that, rather than laying off minimum wage workers, the companies could reduce salaries and bonuses of top-tier employees.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] As in other U.S. territories, the U.S. federal government imposes payroll taxes and the equivalent self-employment tax on income from work in American Samoa, but not the federal income tax on income generated in American Samoa by its residents (except from work as U.S. government employees).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Instead, the government of American Samoa itself taxes the worldwide income of its residents, as well as the income generated there by nonresidents, largely under the same rules and rates as the U.S. tax code in effect in 2000, with certain modifications such as a minimum tax rate of 4%.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] A similar situation applies to corporations.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In 1983, the use of citizenship in taxation by American Samoa (due to its incorporation of the U.S. tax code) was ruled unconstitutional.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] However, these taxes still apply to residents of a U.S. territory who acquired U.S. citizenship by birth or naturalization in a different part of the U.S. or by descent.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] It has been argued that this distinction based on place of birth, and not only residence or citizenship, is a rare case of unconstitutional tax discrimination, but it has never been challenged in court.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The government of American Samoa itself does not impose estate or gift taxes.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] U.S. citizens (or anyone) cannot acquire this status after birth.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa does not impose a sales tax, but it imposes a general import tax of 8%.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is an independent customs territory, whose importation rules and taxes differ from those applicable to other parts of the United States.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Some aspects of telecommunications in American Samoa are, like other U.S. territories, inferior to that of the mainland United States; a recent estimate showed that American Samoa's Internet speed is slower than that of several Eastern European countries.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In 2012 Michael Calabrese, Daniel Calarco, and Colin Richardson stated that American Samoa had the most expensive internet of any U.S. territory and that the speeds were only slightly superior to those of dial-up internet in the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] They also stated that many American Samoans are too poor to afford "high-speed internet".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa has 150 miles (240 km) of highways (estimated in 2008).
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The maximum speed limit is 30 miles per hour.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Ports and harbors include Aunuʻu, Auasi, Faleasao, Ofu and Pago Pago.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The territory has three airports, all of which have paved runways.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The main airport is Pago Pago International Airport, on the island of Tutuila.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The Manuʻa group has two airports: Ofu Airport on the island of Ofu, and Fitiuta Airport on the island of Taʻū.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] According to a 1999 estimate, the territory has no merchant marine.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] On June 8, 1922, the first bus service on Tutuila began its operations.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The *ʻaiga* bus system travels across the island of Tutuila.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] As of 2022, the population of American Samoa is estimated around 45,443 people.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The 2020 census counted 49,710 people, 97.5% of whom lived on the largest island, Tutuila.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] About 57.6% of the population were born in American Samoa, 28.6% in independent Samoa, 6.1% in other parts of the United States, 4.5% in Asia, 2.9% in other parts of Oceania, and 0.2% elsewhere.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] At least 69% of the population had a parent born outside American Samoa.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is small enough to have just one ZIP code, 96799, and uses the U.S.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] Postal Service (state code "AS") for mail delivery.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In the 2020 census, 89.4% of the population reported at least partial Samoan ethnicity, 83.2% only Samoan, 5.8% Asian, 5.5% other Pacific island ethnicities, 4.4% mixed, and 1.1% other ethnicities.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan language was spoken at home by 87.9% of the population, while 6.1% spoke other Pacific island languages, 3.3% spoke English, 2.1% spoke an Asian language, and 0.5% spoke other languages; 47.2% of the population spoke English at home or "very well".
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] In 2022, Samoan and English were designated as official languages of the territory.
[src:american-community-survey/american-samoa-p02] At least some of the deaf population use Samoan Sign Language.
